<paragraph blockId="3.[148,978,1231,1570]" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">
The 
<typeStatus box="[221,308,1364,1385]" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">lectotype</typeStatus>
(SBL 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[382,400,1364,1384]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">¼</emphasis>
<quantity box="[411,506,1364,1385]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1199999999999999" pageId="3" pageNumber="148" unit="mm" value="11.2">11.2 mm</quantity>
; ABL 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[580,598,1364,1384]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">¼</emphasis>
about 
<quantity box="[675,767,1364,1385]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" pageId="3" pageNumber="148" unit="mm" value="13.5">13.5 mm</quantity>
) is conspecific with specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Chaudoir, 1843)" baseAuthorityName="Chaudoir" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[277,576,1390,1411]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="148" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saphyrinus">
<emphasis box="[277,406,1390,1411]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">L. saphyrinus</emphasis>
(Chaudoir, 1843)
</taxonomicName>
[NEW SYNONYMY]. As pointed out by Allen (1972:128), 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Chaudoir" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[268,400,1417,1438]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="148" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saphyrinus">
<emphasis box="[268,400,1417,1438]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">L. saphyrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
‘‘is very distinct.’’ It is the largest species of the genus in North America, though large specimens of a few species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[773,831,1443,1464]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="148" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rectus">
<emphasis box="[773,831,1443,1464]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">rectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[881,977,1443,1464]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">erracticus</emphasis>
groups could reach the size range of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Chaudoir" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[494,623,1470,1491]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="148" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saphyrinus">
<emphasis box="[494,623,1470,1491]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="148">L. saphyrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with a very characteristic pronotum: the sides are evenly rounded, the posterior angles widely rounded, the lateral margins explanate at base in most specimens, the lateral beads indistinct, and the anterior sulcus is not impressed medially.
</paragraph>
